<li>LrhA represses RpoS stability by affecting the function of ClpXP and the response regulator S RssB ( or SprE ) , which serves as a s recognition factor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>We provide evidence that LrhA promotes degradation of RpoS by functioning within a genetic pathway that includes the response regulator SprE and the ClpXP protease .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA functions within the RpoS pathway to alter stationary-phase gene-expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA plays a role in modulating the activity of the RpoS pathway , we wanted to determine whether it functions to vary the levels of RpoS or whether LrhA acts in concert with RpoS to regulate stationary-phase development .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA is closely related to HexA and PecT from plantpathogenic Erwinia species , which function as repressors both of motility and of multiple virulence factors , such as lytic exoenzymes ( Harris et al. , 1998 ; Surgey et al. , 1996 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , the LrhA protein also controls the stationary-phase sigma factor s ( RpoS ) , which regulates S gene-expression in response to general stress in enteric bacteria ( Gibson & Silhavy , 1999 ; Mukherjee et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , HexA , a close relative of LrhA ( > 60 % identity ) from the plant pathogen Erwinia carotovora , negatively regulates the expression of rsmB , a homologue of E. coli csrB ( Mukherjee et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>To test whether additional adhesins and other virulence factors speciﬁc for UPEC strains are also under the control of the LrhA protein , we used the ` E. coli pathoarray ' , which carries 456 DNA probes for typical virulenceassociated genes of extra-intestinal and intestinal patho-genic E. coli , and Shigella ( Dobrindt et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. coli , several global regulators such as H-NS ( Bertin et al. , 1994 ) , OmpR ( Shin & Park , 1995 ) , CRP-cAMP ( Soutourina et al. , 1999 ) , LrhA ( Lehnen et al. , 2002 ) and RcsAB ( Francez-Charlot et al. , 2003 ) are directly involved in the complex genetic regulatory hierarchy that assures ordered assembly of ﬂagellar components .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20528937" target="_blank">20528937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both regulators control further genes that are not in common : FlhD2C2 , the genes of anaerobic electron transport and sugar-transport ( Prüß et al. , 2001 ) ; and LrhA , ﬁmbrial genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA also controls its own expression , but unlike most LysRtype regulators , LrhA is positively autoregulated ( Lehnen et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>0002-8098 G 2005 SGM Differential gene-expression studies have indicated that LrhA also represses structural ( ﬁmAICDFG ) and regulatory ( ﬁmE ) genes related to the synthesis of type 1 ﬁmbriae ( Lehnen et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
